title.narrative: GUATEMALA Maternal and Infant Health and Nutrition

description.narrative: The proposed Project aims to support the Government of Guatemala to: (a) improve maternal and infant health in the project's 40 areas of intervention; and (b) reduce chronic malnutrition among children younger than 2 years of age in the rural areas of the 70 municipalities targeted by the project.

title.narrative: Percentage of mothers receiving post-natal case within 10 days of delivery in the areas of intervention (information to be gatheredfrom CAIMI and PEC).

comment.narrative: Earlier ISR had listed this as 45.54% but that was a typographical error. The PAD and other project docs indicate that this shouldbe 0
Target surpassed.source: SIGSA

title.narrative: Indigenous/non indigenous maternal mortality ratio in project area.

comment.narrative: Source: SIGSA

target.value: Reduce by 10 percent with respect to the baseline.

comment.narrative: Target surpassed. indigenous to non-indigenous MMR reduced to less than half of baseline. Latest available reliable informationsource from National Center of Epidemiology. Most recently available comparable information from SIGSA also show target has beensurpassed in 2010 and 2011 with the ratios being 1.59 and 1.44, respectively.

title.narrative: Number of Secondary level services with cartera ampliada and operating room fully operational.

comment.narrative: Target revised from 8 to 10 to take into account final Project restructuring.
Increased.

title.narrative: Number of secondary level services with cartera ampliada, but without operating room, fully operational.

comment.narrative: Target revised from 32 to 27 to support more areas with more CAIMI to improve access to surgical services than CAP whilemaintaining the total number of rehabilitated health facilities.
Target achieved. The Project supported the rehabilitation of an additional CAP that will only be 80% complete by end of Projectdate which will bring total to 27.8%.

actual.value: 142 jurisdictions (community based) and 8 districts (AINM-C institutional or with health mobile teams)

comment.narrative: Target surpassed. Government supported 142 jurisdictions with AINM-C by financing community educators who link health staff andcommunities through the PEC and the Project continued to support 8 districts with AINM-C "institicional" or with MOH mobile healthteams instead of NGOs

title.narrative: Percentage of families attended by Creciendo Bien in areas of intervention.

comment.narrative: Target nearly achieved.

target almost achieved. This is the latest available updated information.

target.value: Increase by 20 percent with respect to the baseline.

title.narrative: Integrated strategy for the implementation of the three programs.

comment.narrative: As part of the approved restructuring, the 3 programs (PEC, AINM-C, and Cresciendo Bien) were specified.

Target achieved for the 3 programs (AINM-C, PEC, and Cresciendo Bien) especially in terms of an integrated communications strategyand incorporation of the community educators trained in AINM-C in the PEC.

title.narrative: Indigenous/non indigenous infant mortality ratio in project area.

target.value: Reduce by 10 percent with respect to the baseline.

comment.narrative: Final target not achieved. Latest available reliable data is from 2010. Improved from 2009 but slightly higher than 2007 data.

Target almost achieved but by end of Project, remaining CAIMI will be 76% rehabilitated and remaining CAP will be 80% rehabilitated.
Yearly target specified per the approved Project restructuring
Target surpassed.
